    {
      "title": "Half Angle Formula",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Half angle formulae&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>$\\text{sin}\\frac{A}{2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\left( s-b \\right)\\left( s-c \\right)}{bc}}$</p><p>$\\text{cos}\\frac{\\text{A}}{2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{s}\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{a} \\right)}{\\text{bc}}}$</p><p>$\\text{tan}\\frac{\\text{A}}{2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{b} \\right)\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{c} \\right)}{\\text{s}\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{a} \\right)}}=\\frac{\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{b} \\right)\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{c} \\right)}{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }}$</p><p>$\\text{cot}\\frac{\\text{A}}{2}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\text{s}\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{a} \\right)}{\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{b} \\right)\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{c} \\right)}}=\\frac{\\text{s}\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{a} \\right)}{\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }}$</p><p><strong>Tip :</strong> for sine formula, in numerator the other sides are taken and the side opposite to</p><p>the angle is not in the formula.</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }=$ area of triangle $\\text{ABC}=\\sqrt{\\text{s}\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{a} \\right)\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{b} \\right)\\left( \\text{s}-\\text{c} \\right)}$ (Hero's formula)</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }=\\frac{\\text{abc}}{4\\mathbf{R}}$</p><p>The expression for $\\text{sin}\\frac{\\text{B}}{2},\\text{cos}\\frac{\\text{B}}{2},\\text{tan}\\frac{\\text{B}}{2},\\text{cot}\\frac{\\text{B}}{2},\\text{sin}\\frac{\\text{C}}{2},\\text{cos}\\frac{\\text{C}}{2},\\text{tan}\\frac{\\text{C}}{2},\\text{cot}\\frac{\\text{C}}{2}$ can be derived using symmetry.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddacc03b9dcaf1afec34"
    },
    {
      "title": "Value of Sine Angle and Napier's Analogy",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Napier Analogy</strong></h3><p>$\\text{tan}\\frac{B-C}{2}=\\frac{b-c}{b+c}\\text{cot}\\frac{A}{2}$</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddacc03b9dcaf1afec35"
    },
    {
      "title": "m-n Theorem",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>$\\textbf{m}-\\textbf{n}$ theorem&nbsp;</strong></h3><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"271\" height=\"196\">&nbsp;</p><p>If a point $\\text{D}$ divides the side $\\text{BC}$ of $\\vartriangle \\text{ABC}$ internally in the ratio $\\text{m}:\\text{n}$ and</p><p>$\\angle \\text{BAD}=\\alpha ,\\angle \\text{DAC}=$ $\\beta $ and $\\angle \\text{ADC}=\\theta $ then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} \\left( \\text{m}+\\text{n} \\right)\\text{cot}\\theta &amp; ~=\\text{mcot}\\alpha -\\text{ncot}\\beta \\\\ {} &amp; ~=\\text{ncotB}-\\text{mcotC} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>The result can be derived using sine rule in $\\vartriangle \\text{ABD}$ and $\\vartriangle \\text{ADC}$.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0ddadc03b9dcaf1afec36"
    }
  ],
